      <title>China rebuilding its cities into water absorbent urban areas</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANChina plans to address faulty drainage systems, urban flooding and water scarcity by building 'sponge cities'. In 2013, China announced that its major cities would undergo water infrastructure development that would enable them to absorb and process water. The on-going project is called the Sponge City program and began in the Central City of Wuhan in Hubei province.All cities participating in the program have to guarantee that 20 percent of their urban areas have sponge features by 2020. These sponge features must be able to retain 70 percent of the city's stormwater, according to The Guardian.These sponge features include rain gardens, green space, artificial wetlands, swales and new drainage systems.In the city of Wuhan, 20 percent of the city's urban land would cover roughly 170 square kilometers out of its total urban area of 860 square kilometers.The program currently includes 30 cities. The new target requires them to ensure that 80 percent of their urban land will be capable of absorbing and re-using rain and stormwater.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Sponge city; Location of Wuhan, China. 2. Sponge cities must retain 70 percent of their stormwater.3. Sponge features4. Wuhan City, China: how much the sponge city area would coverVOICEOVER (in English): "In 2013, China announced that its major cities would undergo water infrastructure development that would enable them to absorb and process water. The on-going project is called the Sponge City program and began in the Central City of Wuhan in Hubei province.""All cities participating in the program have to guarantee that 20 percent of their urban areas have sponge features by 2020. These sponge features must be able to retain 70 percent of the city's stormwater, reports The Guardian.""These sponge features include rain gardens, green space, artificial wetlands, swales and new drainage systems.""In the city of Wuhan, 20 percent of the city's urban land would cover roughly 170 square kilometers out of its total urban area of 860 square kilometers."SOURCES: The Guardian, Business Insider, Arcadis https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2019/jan/23/inside-chinas-leading-sponge-city-wuhans-war-with-waterhttps://www.businessinsider.com/china-is-building-sponge-cities-that-absorb-water-2017-11https://www.arcadis.com/en/global/what-we-do/our-projects/asia/china/wuhan-sponge-city/***]]></description>
