      <title>FAA demands Boeing improve 737 MAX 8 model</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANUS regulators are demanding Boeing make modifications to improve the 737 MAX 8 following two crashes of the same model.   According to Al Jazeera, the US Federal Aviation Administration is demanding Boeing make improvements to anti-stalling software and the aircrafts' maneuvering system. The FAA has given Boeing until the end of April to finalize the improvements.In an open letter to civil aviation authorities, the FAA stated that Boeing is also updating training requirements and flight crew manuals to go with the new updates to the maneuvering system. These updates include changes to the airplane flight manual, flight crew operations manual and airplane maintenance manual.According to CNN, some airlines are temporarily suspending 737 MAX 8s from flying following last Sunday's crash. These include airlines from China, Singapore, Indonesia, Mexican airline Aeromexico, Argentine airline Aerolneas Argentinas, Cayman Airways and Comair Airways. American Airlines, Southwest Airlines among other airways have announced they will not suspend the aircraft. According to the FAA, there are currently 387 737 MAX 8 and 9 jets flying worldwide, 74 of which are registered in the U.S.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Lionair plane crash2. Ethiopian Airlines crash3. US Federal Aviation Administration demands Boeing make changes4. Boeing updating training requirements and flight crew manuals5. Other manuals that will be updated according to Boeing6. Airlines and countries that have suspended  737 MAX 8VOICEOVER (in English): "In October 2018 an Indonesian plane carrying 188 passengers and crew crashed into the Java Sea. There were no survivors.""Last Sunday, an Ethiopian plane crashed minutes after take-off killing all onboard. Both of these flights were on a Boeing 737 MAX 8 jet.""According to Al Jazeera, the US Federal Aviation Administration is demanding Boeing make improvements to anti-stalling software and the aircrafts' maneuvering system. The FAA has given Boeing until the end of April to finalize the improvements.""In an open letter to civil aviation authorities, the FAA stated that Boeing is also updating training requirements and flight crew manuals to go with the new updates to the maneuvering system." "These updates include changes to the airplane flight manual, flight crew operations manual and airplane maintenance manual.""According to CNN, some airlines are temporarily suspending 737 MAX 8s from flying following last Sunday's crash." "These include airlines from China, Singapore, Indonesia, Mexican airline Aeromexico, Argentine airline Aerolneas Argentinas, Cayman Airways and Comair Airways." "American Airlines, Southwest Airlines among other airways have announced they will not suspend the aircraft." SOURCES: Al Jazeera, Quartz, FAA,  Boeing, CNNhttps://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/regulator-demands-boeing-modify-737-max-ethiopia-crash-190312020507489.htmlhttps://qz.com/1570960/boeing-will-update-the-737-maxs-flight-software-by-april/https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/media/CAN_2019_03.pdfhttps://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=130402\https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2019-01-30-Boeing-Reports-Record-2018-Results-and-Provides-2019-Guidancehttps://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/11/africa/max-8-operations-roundup-intl/index.html***]]></description>
