      <title>Asteroid Bennu found to be rotating faster over time</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANAsteroid Bennu has been found to revolve quicker over time, according to research published in Geophysical Research Letters.NASA's OSIRIS-REx began approaching the asteroid last year. It travelled 2.2 million kilometers from Earth and stationed itself 19 kilometers from Bennu.The discovery was made by ground-based telescopes and the Hubble Space Telescope. Scientists looked at previous data and observed that the asteroid was increasing its rotational speed over time. The OSIRIS-REx spacecraft will independently determine Bennu's speed of rotation by flying closer to the asteroid.Scientists believe that sunlight may be causing Bennu to spin faster as it hits the asteroid from various angles, also known as the YORP effect.The asteroid is traveling across space at 101,000 kilometers per hour and is able to complete a rotation every 4.3 hours. Its speed of rotation has increased around 1 second per century. It is estimated to be around 4.5 billion years old.OSIRIS-REx will collect data and sample the asteroid using the Osiris Visible and Infrared Spectrometer and Osiris Thermal Emission Spectrometer. The spacecraft will use its Touch-and-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism to extract rocks and dirt from the surface of Bennu in July of 2020.It is expected to travel back to Earth and drop off a capsule containing asteroid samples in September 2023.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Asteroid Bennu revolving2. OSIRIS REx approaching the asteroid3. How the discovery was made4. What causes the asteroid to spin faster5. Asteroid in space 6. OSIRIS REx collecting data 7. Spacecraft taking samples 8. Spacecraft going back VOICEOVER (in English): "According to research published in Geophysical Research Letters, asteroid Bennu has been found to revolve quicker over time.""NASA's OSIRIS-REx began approaching the asteroid last year. The spacecraft travelled 2.2 million kilometers from Earth and stationed itself 19 kilometers from Bennu.""The discovery was made via ground-based telescopes and the Hubble Space Telescope.""Scientists looked at data from 1999, 2005 and 2013 and observed that the asteroid was increasing its rotational speed over time.""According to the study, the OSIRIS-REx spacecraft will independently determine Bennu's speed of rotation by flying closer to the asteroid.""The scientists believe that sunlight may be causing Bennu to spin faster as it hits the asteroid from various angles. This is known as the YORP effect.""Asteroid Bennu is currently traveling across space at 101,000 kilometers per hour and is able to complete a rotation every 4.3 hours.""According to the study, Bennu's speed of rotation has increased by around 1 second per century.""The asteroid is estimated to be around 4.5 billion years old.""OSIRIS-REx was sent to collect data and sample the asteroid using the Osiris Visible and Infrared Spectrometer and Osiris Thermal Emission Spectrometer.""The spacecraft will use its Touch-and-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism to extract rocks and dirt from the surface of asteroid Bennu in July of 2020.""It is expected to travel back to Earth and drop off a capsule containing asteroid samples in September 2023." SOURCES: Geophysical Research Letters, Advancing Earth and Space Science press release, NASA, https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2018GL080658https://news.agu.org/press-release/asteroid-bennu-target-of-nasas-sample-return-mission-is-rotating-faster-over-time/https://www.nasa.gov/osiris-rex***]]></description>
